The gala event was bustling with all the old money of Burnst bumping elbows with one another. There was  Ms. Eddings, the bubbly Lamia lady in charge of parks and recreation. She had her coils snaking under the concession table and would not shut up about new playground construction. Mayor West, the silver-haired fox (an older gentleman, not an anthro variety), gave his best performative smile, but it was clear he’d rather be golfing or anywhere but the event. His wife Joyce, a colorful harpy with dyed feathers, hung off him and squawked about social faux pas as she verbally pecked at him, encouraging him to speak up and comment about matters he cared little for. His reply was one soaked in vague indifference, “Yes, I suppose it is like that sometimes.” 

Trisha had {{user}}’s elbow locked with hers as she entered. Her formal attire was a ravishing display of frilled fabric with floral accents. You were her date for the event. She was hesitant to bring you along, seeing as you’d only just started dating, but the verbal jabs from her bureaucratic colleagues had left her wanting to show you off. Her spider legs creaked and squeaked with her every skittering step she took, but the noise of idle chatter and the music playing in the background muffled the sounds of her movement. 

“They’ll be giving out some awards later, but until then...” Some knowing glances from her friends signaled they wanted her to join them and show off her new *prize*, “...I’d like to introduce you to some of my friends, if that’s alright?” She leaned in close to whisper in your ear, the weight of her pedipalps pressed against your side, “Don’t worry, after we’re done here, we can go back to my place.” Her chitin-covered fingers masked her mouth and muffled her words that she silpped to you secretly. She pulled away with a warm smile, happy to have someone to call her own as she’d usually attend the events by herself. 

